  "runtimeMin": 91,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda, joined first by Chris Ryan and then by Adam Nayman, spend the full episode on David Fincher's The Killer, arguing over how much feeling is actually hiding inside all that control.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "The Killer",
      "note": "with Chris Ryan",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Killer",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Michael Fassbender's assassin botches a Paris hit, then works his way down the list of people responsible for the fallout. Andrew Kevin Walker wrote the voiceover-heavy script; Fincher scores nearly every kill to the Smiths off an iPod Nano work playlist. Sean and Amanda call it their favorite movie of the year and read it as a confession dressed up as a thriller; Chris pushes back that it's really about failure, not love."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Adam Nayman on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Killer",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Nayman, who's written a book on Fincher, argues the movie keeps undercutting its own myth of total control. Charles Parnell's character dies before the six to seven minutes Fassbender calculated, and the dog gets the wrong dose. He compares the Tilda Swinton dinner scene to Benjamin Button and calls Fight Club the closest sibling: two movies about sociopaths whose narration insists you're on their side."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
